Over 30 years ago, before the incineration of Altadena and the
Pacific Palisades=E2=80=94before Elon Musk ran wild on X, before Karen Bass=
 and Rick Caruso were in politics, and before climate change became the lef=
t=E2=80=99s doomsday explanation for everything=E2=80=94the chaparral-fleck=
ed mountains of Southern California burned. From Malibu to Eaton Canyon, an=
d down in Laguna Beach, the hot Santa Ana winds fueled wildfires that scorc=
hed tens of thousands of acres and razed hundreds of homes in 1993. Celebri=
ties fled their burning
mansions down narrow canyon roads, running alongside average middle-class h=
omeowners whose places had become a precious source of generational wealth =
thanks to the region=E2=80=99s soaring property values.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Looters prowled the abandoned neighborhoods. Republicans blamed vagrants fo=
r arson=E2=80=94and, indeed, arson was found to be the cause of some of the=
 fires. City and county agencies bickered with each other in
the aftermath. In Laguna, angry victims and greedy developers presaged toda=
y=E2=80=99s D.E.I. finger-pointing, blaming a gay city council member for d=
evoting =E2=80=9Ctoo much attention to AIDS victims and not enough on fire =
protection.=E2=80=9D Eager to rebuild and reclaim their stunning hillside v=
iews of the Pacific, wealthy liberals begged Democratic leaders to neuter t=
he California Coastal Commission and its environmental protections.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I=E2=80=99m cribbing these stories from Ecology of Fear, Mike Davis=E2=80=
=99s seminal book about Los Angeles and =E2=80=9Cthe imagination of disaste=
r,=E2=80=9D which was available on Amazon last week, but has since sold out=
 in the wake of the fires and devil winds that continue to wreak havoc on t=
he Southland. One chapter in particular, =E2=80=9CThe Case for Letting Mali=
bu Burn,=E2=80=9D has been making the rounds out here, partly for its presc=
ience about the current devastation in Los Angeles and
the human blame games that ensue. But his essay is also a reminder that the=
 flames are not solely the result of climate change, which is what the soci=
al media manager at the D.N.C. would like you to believe ( https://x.com/th=
edemocrats/status/1877452315059192299?s=3D46&t=3D3RQW2SgNnh3n-PDrUyDFXA&utm=
_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F13%2F25%29&utm_=
content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F13%2F25%29&utm_me=
dium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a =
). The Los Angeles Basin is its own peculiar ecosystem, veering between wet=
 winters and dry ones, with Santa Ana winds and tinderbox scrub that have
sparked fires every few years since, well, forever.

=C2=A0

Because of its unrivaled beauty, people in Southern California choose to li=
ve on the edge of disaster, alongside the ocean and in the mountains, build=
ing homes in places that human beings might not be meant to live. But they =
build anyway, collecting memories as they live and raise their families her=
e, despite the ambient risk of flames and mudslides and
floods and quakes. Then, when disaster strikes, municipal debates that migh=
t seem tedious elsewhere=E2=80=94about water, insurance, zoning, brush miti=
gation=E2=80=94explode into vicious and intensely personal political battle=
s. As Davis writes in City of Quartz, his other great history of the region=
, =E2=80=9CLos Angeles homeowners =E2=80=A6 love their children, but they l=
ove their property values more.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But another quote grabbed me over
the weekend as I thought about the current state of Los Angeles politics in=
 the wake of the fires, and the dismal response from the city=E2=80=99s Dem=
ocratic mayor, Karen Bass, whose political career is lying somewhere amid t=
he tiny piles of grey ash currently accumulating on the sidewalks and rooft=
ops across her city. Davis quotes an anonymous screenwriter who moved to th=
e Santa Monica Mountains in the =E2=80=9980s. =E2=80=9CI was extraordinaril=
y liberal until I came to Malibu,=E2=80=9D the writer said. =E2=80=9CNow I=
=E2=80=99m a fascist.=E2=80=9D
Indeed, the absolute worst place for a politician to stand in California is=
 between an Angeleno and their extremely valuable property.

Dereliction of Duty
-------------------

People in Los Angeles are, for the most part, focused on helping
their friends and loved ones who lost everything. They are also focused on =
helping strangers. On Sunday night in Arcadia, at a donation center in Sant=
a Anita Park for victims of the Eaton Fire, volunteers at one point had to =
stop accepting donations because there were too many people showing up to h=
elp. All over the city, Angelenos are sheltering pets. Firefighters are doi=
ng the lord=E2=80=99s work. A trio of my friends in Venice raised several t=
housand dollars over Instagram and Venmo to buy supplies
for the firefighters in our neighborhood, just one platoon in an army of he=
roes who have been laying hose up and down the steep, brush-choked ravines =
of the Palisades to fight the blaze.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

My friends showed up at one Venice firehouse with pallets of water, but it =
turned out the firefighters wanted Zyns, Celsius, and breakfast food even m=
ore. So they went back out and bought those, too. Spreadsheets are
being organized for victims and passed around in group chats, listing all t=
hose things you need but don=E2=80=99t think about taking with you when a f=
ire is racing down a hill toward your home: underwear, toys, pet food, blan=
kets, diapers, a yoga mat, something as simple as a nail clipper.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

This sort of fellowship and generosity, unusual for such a sprawling and di=
verse city which remains remarkably
stratified by class and race, is what most people in Los Angeles are focuse=
d on. But there is the obnoxious and inescapable background noise of social=
 media, too, with partisans and clout-chasers rushing to X and TikTok and e=
lsewhere to post about why the fires are the logical outcome in the failed =
dystopia of liberal California. Even the incoming president, himself, could=
n=E2=80=99t resist posting about Gavin =E2=80=9CNewscum=E2=80=9D and Califo=
rnia=E2=80=99s supposedly incompetent leadership, as the death
toll was rising in the nation=E2=80=99s largest state.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Musk tried to prove this out in his own icky way, meeting with local firefi=
ghters on Sunday and streaming it live on X, trying to bait the first respo=
nders into saying they didn=E2=80=99t have enough water to combat the Palis=
ades fire thanks to inept Democrats. But the firefighters wouldn=E2=80=99t =
bite. They told Musk they did, in fact, have enough water. It=E2=80=99s jus=
t
that the blaze was so massive the water system couldn=E2=80=99t sustain the=
 flow. It was an inconvenient truth for Musk, who, like other MAGA screen a=
ddicts last week, couldn=E2=80=99t resist posting about politics, rather th=
an displaying a shred of humanity, even as the first plume of smoke rose up=
 over the mountains. Babies=E2=80=99 cribs were incinerated, while grandpar=
ents watched a lifetime of memories turned into ash. I can report confident=
ly, from multiple sources here on the ground, that most Angelenos would
like the social media brigade to shut the fuck up.

=C2=A0

At the same time, Bass, elected mayor just over two years ago after years i=
n Congress, has emerged as the singular public figure that even liberal Los=
 Angeles is done with. It=E2=80=99s not because she may or may not have cut=
 the fire department budget, or left a reservoir empty, or didn=E2=80=99t d=
o enough to clean up brush and vegetation around the city, although those
questions are fair. Voters in Los Angeles, generally, understand that their=
 mayor has relatively little power compared to executives in other cities=
=E2=80=94that the City Council has the real muscle, and that Los Angeles Co=
unty has its own services and responsibilities that overlap with the city=
=E2=80=99s or operate independently from it. Local government in L.A. is as=
 balkanized as its neighborhoods. People understand there are no easy solut=
ions, and it will take time to learn all the facts about why the
blazes were so ruinous.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The bigger issue=E2=80=94the main issue=E2=80=94is that Bass lost the publi=
c trust in spectacular fashion. The National Weather Service warned of dang=
erous fire conditions on Friday, January 3. Bass knew about it, because we =
all did. If you live in L.A., you got the weather alert, on the news or on =
your phone. The mayor=E2=80=99s office certainly did. Despite that, Bass bo=
arded a plane the following
day for Ghana as part of a delegation attending the inauguration of the cou=
ntry=E2=80=99s president. And as The New York Times reported over the weeke=
nd, Bass had promised during her mayoral campaign never to leave the countr=
y. It got worse on the return trip=E2=80=94a long way home=E2=80=94when a S=
ky News reporter happened upon Bass and an aide at the airport. The reporte=
r asked Bass, repeatedly, to deliver a message to the city. Bass ignored hi=
m, on camera, for 90 painful seconds, in stone-faced
silence. The clip is devastating, a campaign ad ready-made, the moment for =
which she will always be remembered. =E2=80=9CIf it is true that she left t=
he country on a Saturday after the warning came out, that is a dereliction =
of duty,=E2=80=9D Endeavor C.E.O. Ari Emanuel, who donated to Bass=E2=80=99=
s 2022 campaign, told me.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Backers of billionaire real estate developer Rick Caruso=E2=80=94Bass=E2=80=
=99s once and possibly
future rival for mayor=E2=80=94also smell blood in water ahead of next year=
=E2=80=99s election, if a recall doesn=E2=80=99t come first, which is a rea=
l possibility, even though it would require a mountain of verified signatur=
es from Los Angeles voters. But as one Democratic strategist told me, =E2=
=80=9CYou never know. The anger is there.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

UTA superagent Jay Sures, one of Caruso=E2=80=99s biggest donors and loudes=
t
advocates in the 2022 mayor=E2=80=99s race, told me that Bass=E2=80=99s per=
formance has been disqualifying and unforgivable. =E2=80=9CTo me, it=E2=80=
=99s utter incompetence at the highest level with the mayor=E2=80=99s offic=
e,=E2=80=9D Sures told me. =E2=80=9CThe fact that she was not here on stand=
by and ready to go? It=E2=80=99s unforgivable. At the end of the day, we el=
ect leaders who are supposed to represent us and protect us and be there fo=
r us in times of need. That=E2=80=99s what we expect. Information should be=
 forthright and available at a
moment=E2=80=99s notice. Why are we getting all of our alerts from private =
apps? At the end of the day, we don=E2=80=99t need positive words right now=
=2E We need action. We need people=20=
to get in to see their homes.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0

=C2=A0

Newsom, meanwhile, has been all over the news and more or less acting like =
the de facto leader of Los Angeles in the absence of clear and consistent c=
ommunication from the mayor. Even if he comes
off as famously stiff, Newsom has been flooding the zone as people look for=
 direction=E2=80=94meeting with victims, issuing executive orders, sending =
supplies, and saying yes to every interview. Bass? She=E2=80=99s been showi=
ng up at her news conferences, throwing to other officials, and posting eve=
ry so often on social media, with banal talking points that no one wants to=
 hear. =E2=80=9CThese fires across our region have changed lives forever,=
=E2=80=9D went one X post on Saturday. =E2=80=9CThe days ahead will be chal=
lenging
but we WILL get through this crisis, together.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

How, though? Jonathan Vigliotti of CBS News asked Bass at a press conferenc=
e over the weekend how the government can restore trust with locals who =E2=
=80=9Care losing faith.=E2=80=9D Somewhere in her meandering answer, Bass s=
aid that =E2=80=9Csuccess has been reported=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Cwe a=
re not going to let politics divide us.=E2=80=9D Behind her, city officials=
 shuffled around
uncomfortably.

=E2=80=9CShe Isn=E2=80=99t Built for This=E2=80=9D
--------------------------------

The job of the Los Angeles mayor is, in many ways, ceremonial. You
bring a political point of view to City Hall, and you show leadership when =
called upon. But it=E2=80=99s hard to find anyone in Los Angeles media or p=
olitics right now, including loyal Democrats, who thinks that Bass has done=
 either of those things in the last week.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

She came into office promising to be an in-the-weeds problem solver, especi=
ally on homelessness. But now, with Angelenos looking for guidance
and solutions, they=E2=80=99re more likely to get it from the WatchDuty app=
 or a local news anchor or one of the many city and county officials Bass k=
eeps deferring to during the city=E2=80=99s emergency briefings, televised =
sessions that began only after the mayor returned from abroad and the fires=
 had already chewed through thousands of acres and hundreds of homes. =E2=
=80=9CIt feels like she isn=E2=80=99t built for this,=E2=80=9D said one Dem=
ocratic consultant working in California, pointing out that Bass has spent =
her entire career
in the State Assembly and in Congress. =E2=80=9CThis is wartime. This isn=
=E2=80=99t like voting no on some appropriations bill.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I talked to another Democrat who has worked for mayors in other cities, who=
 said that Bass =E2=80=9Chas put on a clinic on what not to do,=E2=80=9D st=
arting with her decision to leave the city while knowing Los Angeles was on=
 the cusp of a tragedy. =E2=80=9CAll mayors are known for two things,=E2=80=
=9D this
Democrat told me. =E2=80=9COne of them you get to choose. And one of them i=
s going to choose you.=E2=80=9D Rudy Giuliani, in New York, chose to enter =
office as a crime fighter. But the crisis of 9/11 chose him. For Bass, the =
crisis not of her choosing was the fires, and she lost her credibility imme=
diately when she refused to say something, anything, at the airport on the =
way back from Ghana. =E2=80=9CThat is now how everybody sees her and will a=
lways see her,=E2=80=9D the Democrat continued. =E2=80=9CShe
obviously made the wrong choice of going in the first place, but she could =
have fixed all that by getting off the plane and at least saying she cared.=
=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

No one is standing up for Bass these days. Kristin Crowley, her own fire ch=
ief, has thrown Bass under the bus in numerous media appearances, accusing =
her of underfunding the department. The city=E2=80=99s controller, a 34-yea=
r-old gadfly C.P.A.
named Kenneth Mejia, sided with Crowley, posting a lengthy social media rev=
iew of Bass=E2=80=99s budget cuts. Meanwhile, Newsom conspicuously copied B=
ass on a letter announcing an investigation into the city=E2=80=99s water r=
esources and fire preparation.

=C2=A0

And Newsom, a former mayor himself, expressed a flash of angry confusion du=
ring a CNN interview with Anderson Cooper in the burning
Palisades last week, saying local officials needed to provide better answer=
s about the response. These are all obvious signals that Bass has zero poli=
tical capital left, much like Joe Biden after his disastrous debate last su=
mmer. Bass has already announced for reelection next year, a race she will =
almost certainly lose, possibly to Caruso, who came close to beating her la=
st time, despite being a former Republican in a deep blue city. At the time=
, Bass didn=E2=80=99t have much of a
campaign message beyond being the next Democrat in line, but she won with t=
he backing of an outside group organized by Hollywood mogul Jeffrey Katzenb=
erg, which ran ads portraying Caruso as a mini-Trump. Barack Obama also gav=
e Bass a final perfunctory lift, endorsing her late in the campaign when Ba=
ss was struggling to close the deal with L.A. voters.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Caruso, who I=E2=80=99m told might run for governor of California next year=
, has been driving the political conversation here since last Tuesday night=
, when the fires began ripping through his own neighborhood of the Palisade=
s. Two years ago, Caruso portrayed Bass as a feckless career politician who=
 lacked any sort of big vision or experience to =E2=80=9Cfix=E2=80=9D Los A=
ngeles. Feeling emboldened last week, Caruso called into FOX11 and lashed t=
he mayor to host Elex Michaelson.
=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve got a mayor that=E2=80=99s out of the country, and w=
e=E2=80=99ve got a city that=E2=80=99s burning, and there=E2=80=99s no reso=
urces to put out fires,=E2=80=9D Caruso proclaimed, immediately going viral=
 once the clip hit X. =E2=80=9CThis is absolute mismanagement by the city.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Again: Firefighters are saying they had enough water, and Caruso himself pr=
otected his gleaming Palisades mall with the help of private firefighters. =
The
truth is still murky. But with Bass doing little to rally the city, frustra=
ted Angelenos are open to whatever Caruso is saying, especially since he ra=
n for mayor, in part, on expanding the fire department=E2=80=99s budget.=C2=
=A0

=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll never know if the outcome here would=E2=80=99ve been=
 any less devastating under different leadership,=E2=80=9D said Josh Porter=
, a Palisades resident who lost his home in the flames last Tuesday,
rushing out of the neighborhood with his two young children and dogs. =E2=
=80=9CBut we know that we elect leaders to lead, especially in times of cri=
sis. It=E2=80=99s been a week since this happened and the city has heard mo=
re from the guy who lost to her than we have from her. Angelenos deserved t=
o hear from a leader to assure them someone was driving the bus. Because it=
 certainly didn=E2=80=99t feel that way.=E2=80=9D Porter told me that his w=
ife was in London at the time the fires exploded, but she got back to LAX f=
rom
