;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Over 30 years ago, before the incineration=
 of Altadena and the
Pacific Palisades=E2=80=94before <strong>Elon Musk </strong>ran wild on X, =
before <strong>Karen Bass</strong> and <strong>Rick Caruso</strong> were in=
 politics, and before climate change became the left=E2=80=99s doomsday exp=
lanation for everything=E2=80=94the chaparral-flecked mountains of Southern=
 California burned. From Malibu to Eaton Canyon, and down in Laguna Beach, =
the hot Santa Ana winds fueled wildfires that scorched tens of thousands of=
 acres and razed hundreds of homes in 1993. Celebrities fled their burning
mansions down narrow canyon roads, running alongside average middle-class h=
omeowners whose places had become a precious source of generational wealth =
thanks to the region=E2=80=99s soaring property values.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Looters prowled the abandoned neighborhoods. Republicans blamed va=
grants for arson=E2=80=94and, indeed, arson was found to be the cause of so=
me of the fires. City and county agencies bickered with each other in
the aftermath. In Laguna, angry victims and greedy developers presaged toda=
y=E2=80=99s D.E.I. finger-pointing, blaming a gay city council member for d=
evoting =E2=80=9Ctoo much attention to AIDS victims and not enough on fire =
protection.=E2=80=9D Eager to rebuild and reclaim their stunning hillside v=
iews of the Pacific, wealthy liberals begged Democratic leaders to neuter t=
he California Coastal Commission and its environmental protections.=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">I=E2=80=99m cribbing these stories from <em>Ecology of =
Fear</em>, <strong>Mike Davis</strong>=E2=80=99s seminal book about Los Ang=
eles and =E2=80=9Cthe imagination of disaster,=E2=80=9D which was available=
 on Amazon last week, but has since sold out in the wake of the fires and d=
evil winds that continue to wreak havoc on the Southland. One chapter in pa=
rticular, =E2=80=9CThe Case for Letting Malibu Burn,=E2=80=9D has been maki=
ng the rounds out here, partly for its prescience about the current devasta=
tion in Los Angeles and
the human blame games that ensue. But his essay is also a reminder that the=
 flames are not solely the result of climate change, which is what the soci=
al media manager at the D.N.C. would <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c=
/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVWXJQcnRVbXVfcGNEU0F1aVAyQT0iLC=
JocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS90aGVkZW1vY3JhdHMvc3RhdHVzLzE4Nzc0NTIzMTUwNTkxO=
TIyOTk_cz00Nlx1MDAyNnQ9M1JRVzJTZ05uaDNuLVBEclV5REZYQVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jYW1wYWln=
bj1UaGUrQmVzdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODElMkYxMyUyRjI=
1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1=
JJQkVSUyslMjgxJTJGMTMlMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwM=
DI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEy=
YSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MjA0MzI4OH0/ae2=
7f249d3e63942167f11e97a0a51ec9177d87a08aa2358bd7af58e79e6e0a8" style=3D"tex=
t-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">like you to believe</a>. The Los Ang=
eles Basin is its own peculiar ecosystem, veering between wet winters and d=
ry ones, with Santa Ana winds and tinderbox scrub that have
sparked fires every few years since, well, forever.</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Bec=
ause of its unrivaled beauty, people in Southern California choose to live =
on the edge of disaster, alongside the ocean and in the mountains, building=
 homes in places that human beings might not be meant to live. But they bui=
ld anyway, collecting memories as they live and raise their families here, =
despite the ambient risk of flames and mudslides and
floods and quakes. Then, when disaster strikes, municipal debates that migh=
t seem tedious elsewhere=E2=80=94about water, insurance, zoning, brush miti=
gation=E2=80=94explode into vicious and intensely personal political battle=
s. As Davis writes in <em>City of Quartz, </em>his other great history of t=
he region, =E2=80=9CLos Angeles homeowners =E2=80=A6 love their children, b=
ut they love their property values more.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">But another quote=
 grabbed me over
the weekend as I thought about the current state of Los Angeles politics in=
 the wake of the fires, and the dismal response from the city=E2=80=99s Dem=
ocratic mayor, Karen Bass, whose political career is lying somewhere amid t=
he tiny piles of grey ash currently accumulating on the sidewalks and rooft=
ops across her city. Davis quotes an anonymous screenwriter who moved to th=
e Santa Monica Mountains in the =E2=80=9980s. =E2=80=9CI was extraordinaril=
y liberal until I came to Malibu,=E2=80=9D the writer said. =E2=80=9CNow I=
=E2=80=99m a fascist.=E2=80=9D
Indeed, the absolute worst place for a politician to stand in California is=
 between an Angeleno and their extremely valuable property.</p></div>
