alt:
28.799999999999997px;"><strong>Dereliction of Duty</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">People in Los Angeles are, for the most part, f=
ocused on helping
their friends and loved ones who lost everything. They are also focused on =
helping strangers. On Sunday night in Arcadia, at a donation center in Sant=
a Anita Park for victims of the Eaton Fire, volunteers at one point had to =
stop accepting donations because there were too many people showing up to h=
elp. All over the city, Angelenos are sheltering pets. Firefighters are doi=
ng the lord=E2=80=99s work. A trio of my friends in Venice raised several t=
housand dollars over Instagram and Venmo to buy supplies
for the firefighters in our neighborhood, just one platoon in an army of he=
roes who have been laying hose up and down the steep, brush-choked ravines =
of the Palisades to fight the blaze.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">My friends s=
howed up at one Venice firehouse with pallets of water, but it turned out t=
he firefighters wanted Zyns, Celsius, and breakfast food even more. So they=
 went back out and bought those, too. Spreadsheets are
being organized for victims and passed around in group chats, listing all t=
hose things you need but don=E2=80=99t think about taking with you when a f=
ire is racing down a hill toward your home: underwear, toys, pet food, blan=
kets, diapers, a yoga mat, something as simple as a nail clipper.=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">This sort of fellowship and generosity, unusual for such a=
 sprawling and diverse city which remains remarkably
stratified by class and race, is what most people in Los Angeles are focuse=
d on. But there is the obnoxious and inescapable background noise of social=
 media, too, with partisans and clout-chasers rushing to X and TikTok and e=
lsewhere to post about why the fires are the logical outcome in the failed =
dystopia of liberal California. Even the incoming president, himself, could=
n=E2=80=99t resist posting about <strong>Gavin </strong>=E2=80=9CNewscum=E2=
=80=9D and California=E2=80=99s supposedly incompetent leadership, as the d=
eath
toll was rising in the nation=E2=80=99s largest state.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">Musk tried to prove this out in his own icky way, meeting with local =
firefighters on Sunday and streaming it live on X, trying to bait the first=
 responders into saying they didn=E2=80=99t have enough water to combat the=
 Palisades fire thanks to inept Democrats. But the firefighters wouldn=E2=
=80=99t bite. They told Musk they did, in fact, have enough water. It=E2=80=
=99s just
that the blaze was so massive the water system couldn=E2=80=99t sustain the=
 flow. It was an inconvenient truth for Musk, who, like other MAGA screen a=
ddicts last week, couldn=E2=80=99t resist posting about politics, rather th=
an displaying a shred of humanity, even as the first plume of smoke rose up=
 over the mountains. Babies=E2=80=99 cribs were incinerated, while grandpar=
ents watched a lifetime of memories turned into ash. I can report confident=
ly, from multiple sources here on the ground, that most Angelenos would
like the social media brigade to shut the fuck up.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">At t=
he same time, Bass, elected mayor just over two years ago after years in Co=
ngress, has emerged as the singular public figure that even liberal Los Ang=
eles is done with. It=E2=80=99s not because she may or may not have cut the=
 fire department budget, or left a reservoir empty, or didn=E2=80=99t do en=
ough to clean up brush and vegetation around the city, although those
questions are fair. Voters in Los Angeles, generally, understand that their=
 mayor has relatively little power compared to executives in other cities=
=E2=80=94that the City Council has the real muscle, and that Los Angeles Co=
unty has its own services and responsibilities that overlap with the city=
=E2=80=99s or operate independently from it. Local government in L.A. is as=
 balkanized as its neighborhoods. People understand there are no easy solut=
ions, and it will take time to learn all the facts about why the
blazes were so ruinous.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The bigger issue=E2=80=
=94the main issue=E2=80=94is that Bass lost the public trust in spectacular=
 fashion. The National Weather Service warned of dangerous fire conditions =
on Friday, January 3. Bass knew about it, because we all did. If you live i=
n L.A., you got the weather alert, on the news or on your phone. The mayor=
=E2=80=99s office certainly did. Despite that, Bass boarded a plane the fol=
lowing
day for Ghana as part of a delegation attending the inauguration of the cou=
ntry=E2=80=99s president. And as <em>The New York Times </em>reported over =
the weekend, Bass had promised during her mayoral campaign <em>never</em> t=
o leave the country. It got worse on the return trip=E2=80=94a long way hom=
e=E2=80=94when a Sky News reporter happened upon Bass and an aide at the ai=
rport. The reporter asked Bass, repeatedly, to deliver a message to the cit=
y. Bass ignored him, on camera, for 90 painful seconds, in stone-faced
silence. The clip is devastating, a campaign ad ready-made, the moment for =
which she will always be remembered. =E2=80=9CIf it is true that she left t=
he country on a Saturday after the warning came out, that is a dereliction =
of duty,=E2=80=9D Endeavor C.E.O. <strong>Ari Emanuel</strong>, who donated=
 to Bass=E2=80=99s 2022 campaign, told me.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Backer=
s of billionaire real estate developer Rick Caruso=E2=80=94Bass=E2=80=99s o=
nce and possibly
future rival for mayor=E2=80=94also smell blood in water ahead of next year=
=E2=80=99s election, if a recall doesn=E2=80=99t come first, which is a rea=
l possibility, even though it would require a mountain of verified signatur=
es from Los Angeles voters. But as one Democratic strategist told me, =E2=
=80=9CYou never know. The anger is there.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">UTA superagent <strong>Jay Sures</strong>, one of Caruso=E2=80=99s=
 biggest donors and loudest
advocates in the 2022 mayor=E2=80=99s race, told me that Bass=E2=80=99s per=
formance has been <em>disqualifying</em> and <em>unforgivable</em>. =E2=80=
=9CTo me, it=E2=80=99s utter incompetence at the highest level with the may=
or=E2=80=99s office,=E2=80=9D Sures told me. =E2=80=9CThe fact that she was=
 not here on standby and ready to go? It=E2=80=99s unforgivable. At the end=
 of the day, we elect leaders who are supposed to represent us and protect =
us and be there for us in times of need. That=E2=80=99s what we expect. Inf=
ormation should be forthright and available at a
moment=E2=80=99s notice. Why are we getting all of our alerts from private =
apps? At the end of the day, we don=E2=80=99t need positive words right now=
=2E We need action. We need people=20=
to get in to see their homes.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Newsom, meanwhile, has been all over the news and m=
ore or less acting like the <em>de facto</em> leader of Los Angeles in the =
absence of clear and consistent communication from the mayor. Even if he co=
mes
off as famously stiff, Newsom has been flooding the zone as people look for=
 direction=E2=80=94meeting with victims, issuing executive orders, sending =
supplies, and saying <em>yes</em> to every interview. Bass? She=E2=80=99s b=
een showing up at her news conferences, throwing to other officials, and po=
sting every so often on social media, with banal talking points that no one=
 wants to hear. =E2=80=9CThese fires across our region have changed lives f=
orever,=E2=80=9D went one X post on Saturday. =E2=80=9CThe days ahead will =
be challenging
but we WILL get through this crisis, together.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">How, thou=
gh? <strong>Jonathan Vigliotti</strong> of CBS News asked Bass at a press c=
onference over the weekend how the government can restore trust with locals=
 who =E2=80=9Care losing faith.=E2=80=9D Somewhere in her meandering answer=
, Bass said that =E2=80=9Csuccess has been reported=E2=80=9D and that =E2=
=80=9Cwe are not going to let politics divide us.=E2=80=9D Behind her, city=
 officials shuffled around
uncomfortably.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
