t:24px;padding-right:24px;text-align:center;width:100%;"><h3 style=3D"margi=
n:0;color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;PuckSerifDisplay&#39;,&#39=
;Georgia&#39;;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:normal;line-hei=
ght:120%;text-align:center;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;mso-line-height-alt=
:
28.799999999999997px;"><strong>=E2=80=9CShe Isn=E2=80=99t Built for This=E2=
=80=9D</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The job of the Los Angeles mayor is, in many wa=
ys, ceremonial. You
bring a political point of view to City Hall, and you show leadership when =
called upon. But it=E2=80=99s hard to find anyone in Los Angeles media or p=
olitics right now, including loyal Democrats, who thinks that Bass has done=
 either of those things in the last week.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">She cam=
e into office promising to be an in-the-weeds problem solver, especially on=
 homelessness. But now, with Angelenos looking for guidance
and solutions, they=E2=80=99re more likely to get it from the WatchDuty app=
 or a local news anchor or one of the many city and county officials Bass k=
eeps deferring to during the city=E2=80=99s emergency briefings, televised =
sessions that began only after the mayor returned from abroad and the fires=
 had already chewed through thousands of acres and hundreds of homes. =E2=
=80=9CIt feels like she isn=E2=80=99t built for this,=E2=80=9D said one Dem=
ocratic consultant working in California, pointing out that Bass has spent =
her entire career
in the State Assembly and in Congress. =E2=80=9CThis is wartime. This isn=
=E2=80=99t like voting <em>no</em> on some appropriations bill.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I talked to another Democrat who has worked for may=
ors in other cities, who said that Bass =E2=80=9Chas put on a clinic on wha=
t not to do,=E2=80=9D starting with her decision to leave the city while kn=
owing Los Angeles was on the cusp of a tragedy. =E2=80=9CAll mayors are kno=
wn for two things,=E2=80=9D this
Democrat told me. =E2=80=9COne of them you get to choose. And one of them i=
s going to choose you.=E2=80=9D <strong>Rudy Giuliani</strong>, in New York=
, chose to enter office as a crime fighter. But the crisis of 9/11 chose hi=
m. For Bass, the crisis not of her choosing was the fires, and she lost her=
 credibility immediately when she refused to say something, <em>anything</e=
m>, at the airport on the way back from Ghana. =E2=80=9CThat is now how eve=
rybody sees her and will always see her,=E2=80=9D the Democrat continued. =
=E2=80=9CShe
obviously made the wrong choice of going in the first place, but she could =
have fixed all that by getting off the plane and at least saying she cared.=
=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">No one is standing up for Bass these days. <s=
trong>Kristin Crowley</strong>, her own fire chief, has thrown Bass under t=
he bus in numerous media appearances, accusing her of underfunding the depa=
rtment. The city=E2=80=99s controller, a 34-year-old gadfly C.P.A.
named <strong>Kenneth Mejia</strong>, sided with Crowley, posting a lengthy=
 social media review of Bass=E2=80=99s budget cuts. Meanwhile, Newsom consp=
icuously copied Bass on a letter announcing an investigation into the city=
=E2=80=99s water resources and fire preparation.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">And Ne=
wsom, a former mayor himself, expressed a flash of angry confusion during a=
 CNN interview with <strong>Anderson Cooper</strong> in the burning
Palisades last week, saying local officials needed to provide better answer=
s about the response. These are all obvious signals that Bass has zero poli=
tical capital left, much like <strong>Joe Biden </strong>after his disastro=
us debate last summer. Bass has already announced for reelection next year,=
 a race she will almost certainly lose, possibly to Caruso, who came close =
to beating her last time, despite being a former Republican in a deep blue =
city. At the time, Bass didn=E2=80=99t have much of a
campaign message beyond being the next Democrat in line, but she won with t=
he backing of an outside group organized by Hollywood mogul <strong>Jeffrey=
 Katzenberg</strong>, which ran ads portraying Caruso as a mini-<strong>Tru=
mp</strong>. <strong>Barack Obama</strong> also gave Bass a final perfuncto=
ry lift, endorsing her late in the campaign when Bass was struggling to clo=
se the deal with L.A. voters.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">Caruso, who I=E2=80=99m told might run for governor of =
California next year, has been driving the political conversation here sinc=
e last Tuesday night, when the fires began ripping through his own neighbor=
hood of the Palisades. Two years ago, Caruso portrayed Bass as a feckless c=
areer politician who lacked any sort of big vision or experience to =E2=80=
=9Cfix=E2=80=9D Los Angeles. Feeling emboldened last week, Caruso called in=
to FOX11 and lashed the mayor to host<strong> Elex Michaelson</strong>.
=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve got a mayor that=E2=80=99s out of the country, and w=
e=E2=80=99ve got a city that=E2=80=99s burning, and there=E2=80=99s no reso=
urces to put out fires,=E2=80=9D Caruso proclaimed, immediately going viral=
 once the clip hit X. =E2=80=9CThis is absolute mismanagement by the city.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Again: Firefighters are<em> saying</em>=
 they had enough water, and Caruso himself protected his gleaming Palisades=
 mall with the help of private firefighters. The
truth is still murky. But with Bass doing little to rally the city, frustra=
ted Angelenos are open to whatever Caruso is saying, especially since he ra=
n for mayor, in part, on expanding the fire department=E2=80=99s budget.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;">=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll never know if the outcome here would=E2=80=99v=
e been any less devastating under different leadership,=E2=80=9D said <stro=
ng>Josh Porter</strong>, a Palisades resident who lost his home in the flam=
es last Tuesday,
rushing out of the neighborhood with his two young children and dogs. =E2=
=80=9CBut we know that we elect leaders to lead, especially in times of cri=
sis. It=E2=80=99s been a week since this happened and the city has heard mo=
re from the guy who lost to her than we have from her. Angelenos deserved t=
o hear from a leader to assure them someone was driving the bus. Because it=
 certainly didn=E2=80=99t feel that way.=E2=80=9D Porter told me that his w=
ife was in London at the time the fires exploded, but she got back to LAX f=
rom
overseas before the mayor did.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
